Makes Homer string his lyre, and Milton ape his jest The reverend Editor proves, in his manner, that numberless passages, in the Battle of Hastings, are not only borrowed from the original Greek of Homer, but also greatly im∣proved. In the same way he has, with peculiar sagacity, found out, "that the grave Milton, in his PENSEROSO, amused himself by reflecting on the buskin'd tale of Chaucer in these lines:
Or call up him that left half-told
The story of Cambuscan bold. Just as Rowley had reflected on him before for not finishing his stories. See note on the Epistle to Mastre Canynge, p. 167. O ye venerable Society of Antiquarians, whatever ye in your wisdom shall think fit to do with the rest of your President's notes, inscribe this, I beseech you, in letters of gold over your new chimney-piece at Somerset House.;
